'''Kohaku Shrine''' (こはくじんじゃ) is a Shinto shrine near {{ill|lt=Jindaiji|Q500736|qid=Q500736|1=Jindai-ji (Tokyo)}} in Sasu-cho, {{ill|lt=Chofu|Q210667|qid=Q210667|1=Chōfu}}, {{ill|lt=Tokyo|Q1490|qid=Q1490|1=Tokyo}}. It enshrines Otoshi Mioya no Kami. It is a candidate for the Engishiki shrine "Kohaku Shrine" of Tama District, Musashi Province, and was formerly ranked as a gosha and tutelary shrine of old Sasu Village.

=== History ===
According to shrine tradition, the shrine was founded in 588 by enshrining Otoshi Mioya no Kami. {{sfn|新編武蔵風土記稿 佐須村}}

Traditions connected with Jindaiji state that Manko Shonin's grandparents were worshiped here as guardian deities of Jindaiji.<ref name="jindaiji">''Jindaiji Engi''.</ref> The shrine name "Kohaku" is linked to stories about his grandmother "Tora" and grandfather "Ukon" and the old place-name "Komano-no-sato."<ref name="jindaiji"/>

In later centuries, Gion-ji (Kohakusan Nikko-in), founded by Manko Shonin, served as the shrine's betto temple until the Edo period.

; Shrine rank
* {{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|qid=Q7757|1=1873}} - designated {{ill|lt=gosha|Q134917316|qid=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}.<ref name="kitatama">''Kitatama Jinjashi'' (Kitatama Shinto Youth Association Murasaki-kai, 1976).</ref>

